docs.abstract: The recent volatility in the stock market can make older investors feel vulnerable. Here are some strategies to make sure your money lasts as long as you do.
docs.snippet: The recent volatility in the stock market can make older investors feel vulnerable. Here are some strategies to make sure your money lasts as long as you do.
docs.lead_paragraph: You’ve heard it before: When the markets become erratic, or seem poised for a prolonged downturn, the best thing you can do is nothing at all.

headline.main: How to Dodge a Market Dip That Threatens Your Retirement
headline.print_headline: Retirement Investing Tips in Market Gone Awry

docs.abstract: Federal prosecutors in New Jersey said the men had breached a Securities and Exchange Commission database to obtain information about companies that was not yet public.

docs.lead_paragraph: Companies use the Securities and Exchange Commission’s corporate filing system to share market-moving news with investors and the public. Getting an early peek at those filings would be very helpful to a thief.

docs.abstract: A year after his annual letter to chief executives urged them to run their companies with the social good in mind, the BlackRock chief Larry Fink said they must step into a leadership vacuum.
docs.snippet: A year after his annual letter to chief executives urged them to run their companies with the social good in mind, the BlackRock chief Larry Fink said they must step into a leadership vacuum.
docs.lead_paragraph: Larry Fink, the investment manager who oversees nearly $6 trillion at BlackRock, set off a yearlong conversation among business leaders and policymakers last January when he wrote a letter to chief executives declaring that companies needed to do more than make profits.

headline.main: World’s Biggest Investor Tells C.E.O.s Purpose Is the ‘Animating Force’ for Profits
headline.print_headline: Top Investor Says C.E.O.s Can Bridge Global Rifts

docs.abstract: The percentage of minorities and women serving as directors of America’s largest public companies has risen since 2016, but white men still dominate, the Alliance for Board Diversity found.
docs.snippet: The percentage of minorities and women serving as directors of America’s largest public companies has risen since 2016, but white men still dominate, the Alliance for Board Diversity found.
docs.lead_paragraph: The percentage of minorities and women on the boards of the largest public companies in the United States has edged up in the last two years, but “advancement is still slow” and the bulk of corporate directors at such firms continue to be white men, a study released on Tuesday finds.

headline.main: Slow Gains for Women and Minorities on Boards of Big U.S. Firms, Study Says
headline.print_headline: Slow Gains for Women and Minorities on U.S. Boards

docs.abstract: Writers and editors talk about Adam Moss, the editor of New York magazine, who announced on Tuesday that he is stepping down after leading the publication for 15 years.
docs.snippet: Writers and editors talk about Adam Moss, the editor of New York magazine, who announced on Tuesday that he is stepping down after leading the publication for 15 years.
docs.lead_paragraph: Adam Moss’s decision to step down after 15 years as editor in chief of New York sent ripples through the magazine world. The New York Times spoke with peers and colleagues about his career and influence. Their remarks have been edited for length and clarity.

headline.main: ‘He’s the Best, He’s the Best, He’s the Best’
headline.print_headline: ‘He’s the Best, He’s the Best, He’s the Best’

docs.abstract: Mr. Ghosn, detained since November on allegations of financial misconduct, now faces months of additional jail time as his case heads to court.
docs.snippet: Mr. Ghosn, detained since November on allegations of financial misconduct, now faces months of additional jail time as his case heads to court.
docs.lead_paragraph: TOKYO — A Tokyo court on Tuesday denied bail to Carlos Ghosn, the former Nissan chairman detained since November on allegations of financial misconduct. The embattled auto chief now faces two more months in a jail cell — and possibly longer — as his case heads to court.

headline.main: Carlos Ghosn, Former Nissan Chairman, Is Denied Bail in Japan
headline.print_headline: Bail Denial May Keep Ghosn in Jail For Months

docs.abstract: Mr. Moonves was fired for cause by the company’s board following numerous allegations of sexual misconduct. He denies them, and wants his lucrative exit payment.
docs.snippet: Mr. Moonves was fired for cause by the company’s board following numerous allegations of sexual misconduct. He denies them, and wants his lucrative exit payment.
docs.lead_paragraph: Leslie Moonves, the former chief executive of CBS, plans to fight a decision by the company’s board that denied him a $120 million severance payment after he was fired for cause following numerous allegations of sexual misconduct.

docs.abstract: The verdict is the latest in a series of lawsuits over accusations that the company’s powder products contained asbestos and caused a consumer’s cancer.
docs.snippet: The verdict is the latest in a series of lawsuits over accusations that the company’s powder products contained asbestos and caused a consumer’s cancer.
docs.lead_paragraph: A New Jersey jury ruled unanimously for Johnson & Johnson on Wednesday in the latest lawsuit to reach a verdict over accusations that the company’s talc-based powder products contained asbestos and caused a consumer’s cancer.

headline.main: Johnson & Johnson Cleared by New Jersey Jury in Latest Talc Cancer Trial
headline.print_headline: Jurors Clear Powder Maker At Cancer Trial In New Jersey
